## 6) variables to label the plots for NY TIMES

variable_names <- list(
  "cases_CA" = "Total Cases" ,
  "deaths_CA" = "Total Deaths"
)

variable_labeller <- function(variable, value){
  return(variable_names[value])
}

## 6b) variables to label the plots for CSSE
variable_names2 <- list(
  "csse_cases" = "Total Cases" ,
  "csse_deaths" = "Total Deaths"
)

variable_labeller2 <- function(variable, value){
  return(variable_names2[value])}
  
## 7) PLOT FOR NY TIMES DATA 
CA_plot_Times <- CA_plot_data_Times %>% ggplot(
  aes(x = date,
      y = number_reported,
      fill = type,
      color = type)) +
         geom_bar(stat = 'identity',
                  size = .2, na.rm = TRUE)+
 facet_wrap(~ type,
             nrow =  2, 
             scales = "free",
             labeller = variable_labeller) + 
  labs(x = "Date", 
       y = "Total Deaths NY Times        Total Cases CSSE", 
       fill = "Type Reported:") +
  theme(title = element_text(face = "bold",
                             size = 10),
        axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1), 
        axis.title.y = element_text(face = "bold"),
        axis.title.x = element_text(face = "bold"),
        legend.position = "none") +
  ggplot2::labs(title =
              "    California COVID-19, via NY Times") + 
  scale_fill_discrete(labels = c("Cases", "Deaths")) +
  scale_x_date(date_labels = "%b %Y", 
               date_breaks = "3 months",
               limits = as.Date(c('2020-03-15','2022-10-15')))

Communicate your methodology, results, and interpretation here First, the CSSE data set was very different to work with. I dont understand why someone would save the date as a character class. So we fixed that and fixed how the cases and deaths were spread across the columns using pivot_longer(). Then the global population data set was weird too, like the population estimate itself was a character class, when it was numbers obviously and instead of using NA or 0 for unknown population estimate it had .. so I couldnt convert is using as_numeric() easily. Anyways, I used a for loop to convert it instead because it got the job done even though there is probably a shortcut function. Then we needed to find where the two data sets had the same countries. We did this using a nested for loop because we needed to find if there were any matches regardless of position, so for each iteration of the COVID data set, we checked all of the population data set. This is probably taxing on the computer, but it was the tried and true method. Next, despite finding where there were matches, we needed it as a list character in order to use it in an indexing format. We kept only the values for countries found in both data sets, and yet Eritrea snuck in there without an acutal pop. estimate so we filtered it out individually. Finally we combined the data sets because they finally matched in observations and we calculated, saving the new variable with mutate(). The results of the top 10 countries seem to match my results through Google searching. Although these countries are not highly populated nor did they have the most number of total COVID deaths and cases, they have higher rates per capital due to lack of medical resources. The John Hopkins University website has a COVID data page where the deaths per 100k for Peru is 659, which is close to our results. The page similarly has Bulgaria, Hungary, and our other countries we found as the top 10 listed within reasonable proximity to ours. Noting that theres may by higher because the results are up to the current date.

Construct a visualization plotting the 10 countries in terms of deaths and cases per 100,000 people between March 15, 2020, and December 31, 2021. In designing your visualization keep the number of data you will be plotting in mind. You may wish to create two separate visualizations, one for deaths and another for cases.

## 1) Gather the COVID 19 data for only the top 10 countries 
## 1b) based on our previous tidying

csse_10_tidy2 <- csse_10_tidy[csse_10_tidy$country

## 3) set the date lower and upper bounds

global_pop_again <- global_population_estimates

## 5) Now, to work with the populations we need to change the class to numeric
## we'll use the same for loop method as before, once for the
## 5b) first for the 2020 pop. 
top_10_pop_2020_as_num <- 
    vector("double", length(top_10_pop_tidy$pop_est_2020))
  for(i in 1:length(top_10_pop_tidy$pop_est_2020)){
    top_10_pop_2020_as_num[i] <- as.numeric(top_10_pop_tidy$pop_est_2020[i])
  }
## 5c) the for the 2021 pop. 
top_10_pop_2021_as_num <- 
  vector("double", length(top_10_pop_tidy$pop_est_2021))

  top_10_pop_2021_as_num[i] <- as.numeric(top_10_pop_tidy$pop_est_2021[i])
}

## 7) Combine the COVID tidy set with the pop. tidy set

  ## top_10_pop_tidy
  ## csse_10_tidy2
  ## verify that new data set is correct

  )

## 8) use a for loop to calc. cases per 100k 

cases_by100k <- vector("double", 6570)
for (i in 1:6570){
  if(substr(ten_by_100k$date[i], 1, 4) == "2020"){
    cases_by100k[i] <- (ten_by_100k$cases[i] / ten_by_100k$num_2020[i]*100000)
  }
  else{
    cases_by100k[i] <- (ten_by_100k$cases[i] / ten_by_100k$num_2021[i]*100000)
  }
}

## 9) use another for loop to calculate deaths per 100k
deaths_by100k <- vector("double", 6570)
for (i in 1:6570){
  if(substr(ten_by_100k$date[i], 1, 4) == "2020"){
    deaths_by100k[i] <- (ten_by_100k$deaths[i] / ten_by_100k$num_2020[i]*100000)
  }
  else{

  }
